        <hr noshade size="1">
        
        <font color="white" face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size="2">Dire charm is fun fun fun!  Level cap has not really been an issue, lots of zones you can use it in.  Not much difference in a pet that hits for 115 vs. one that hits for 120 in most situations anyhow.  If your grouping, they also very rarely take agro since they have nice hitpoints and they can't taunt.  </P><P>I've largely been thinking lifeburn is not all its cracked up to be.</P><P>When soloing, I have 2050 hit points so that would equate to about 1500 points of damage of dd on a lifeburn.  (the rest of the damage is on a 250 per tick bond effect that lasts for 6 ticks) Then I'm stuck at 1 hit point, so I am probably going to want to click off demi lich, and going to want to feign, harmshield, touch of night, whatever to get my hit points back to a point where I won't immediately die if something should hit me.</P><P>Considering I am almost never at full hit points thanks to demi lich even when in groups or raids, I don't see much value in it.  Now a crit on a lifeburn with buffed hit points would be most impressive in a raid situation, but I'll let the wizards dd, and I'll stick to my dots.</P><P>I used to really hate the idea of lifeburn because I assumed the timers did not count down while you were offline.  But they do, so the 144 minute timer is not as bad, especially if you play in short shifts.  </P><P>But I would say other skills, like dire charm, fearstorm, innate invis vs. undead (very useful especially if you have to feign around undead) would be a better way to spend your points to start with.  Lots of arch skills would be great to.  Personally I went with spell casting mastery, but I plan to get channeling focus and then either the no fizzles or spell casting fury.  (largely because they would be good things to have for duelling)</P><P><BR><img src="http://www.users.qwest.net/~morbid909/ezboardsig.jpg" border=0><br>Those who have turned away, shall be turned upon.<BR> <br>Ravanta 